amines the structure of New York City’s German community in terms of its maturity, geographic dispersal from the Lower East Side to other neighborhoods, and its ultimate assimilation to the point of invisibility in the 1920s. It argues that when confronted with the anti-German feelings of World War I, German immigrants and German Americans hid their culture – especially their language and their institutions – behind closed doors and sought to make themselves invisible while still existing as a German community. But becoming invisible did not mean being absorbed into an Anglo-American English-speaking culture and society. Instead, German Americans adopted visible behaviors of a new, more pluralistic American culture that they themselves had helped to create, although by no means dominated. Just as the meaning of “German” changed in this period, so did the meaning of “American” change as well, due to nearly 100 years of German immigration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 0aGerman AmericansxCultural assimilationzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aGerman AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aGerman AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aGerman, Germans in the US, immigrants, German immigrant, New York City, Germans in New York City, German communities, German Americans, anti-German, Lower East Side, World War 1, Germany, assimilation, Kleindeutschland, Little Germany, Dutchtown, East Village, Manhattan.40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197882322840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978823228423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978823228/original  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPD